climbs.name: Zombie Woof (submitted as Big Hands Roof)
climbs.fa: Dave Henritze, Jim Olsen, Jim N, and others, 1980s

content.description: This is a great long route that puts a bit of hurt on you through a small roof and up wide hands/fists. Be careful on the lower section. Your belayer may want to plug something into the Chinle as you are perched on a bit of a knoll.
content.protection: Bring a yellow Metolius, some other fingers at the bottom, doubles from #0.75 to #3, maybe triples of #3, and 1 or 2 #4s.
content.location:
This is climber's right of

The Curve

and across the drainage approximately 250 feet. Start at the top of the opposite drainage and traverse some Chinle to begin the crack.

content.description: This is an awesome route that goes through varied and unique moves. It is not your typical plug and play. The crux comes at the top! It is short but engaging and just plain fun!
content.protection: Bring singles of #1 and #2, doubles from #0.75-#0.3 Camalot, one or two small (blue Metolius and/or green C3).
content.location:
This is 40 feet to the right of

Short, Some Hands

up the obvious, thin splitter.

content.description: This is a great, short climb on excellent stone. It is a good introduction to the art of the layback.
content.protection: Doubles of fingers, a #4 for the start, and smaller towards the end.
content.location:
This is three feet right of the

Moderation

.

climbs.name: Slightly Overhanging Wide Corner (unknown no plaque)

content.description:
Just a few feet to the right of

Hanging to the Right

, the beautiful but silty dihedral climbs to anchors just after a slight overhang.
content.protection: A couple of 3 inch to 4.5 inch pieces.

content.description: Climb a few feet of choss to gain the splitter corner that widens to hand and fists towards the top. Nearing the anchor, it becomes wide and blocky.
content.protection: Singles #1-#3, doubles in #4 Camalot.
content.location:
This is 30 feet to the right of

OW Corner

.

content.description:
Just 30 (or so) feet to the right of the

Big Hands Roof

is a dihedral. The climbing is broken by a huge ledge, but it is still fun. There are a couple ways to get to the ledge.
content.protection: A double set of cams from 0.5 - 3 inch should do whichever way you choose.

content.description: This has sustained climbing through fingers in an acute corner with periodic stem rests. The crux coming through and pulling over the #0.5 roof. A few more strenuous moves get you to a decent rest and an awkward move to the anchors. If it wasn't for the light colored rock, this would be a classic!
content.protection: Singles of #1 Camalot #0.75, 6-7 #0.5.
content.location:
This is 30 feet right of

Hands to OW

identified by the obvious 4 foot roof.

content.description: This is a good, wide corner that starts off big hands, goes to fists, and to stacked hands towards the top. The section where you pull through the bulge on fists and when it gets near the top seem to be the cruxes.
content.protection: Bring doubles of #4, #5. Maybe a #6 at the top.
content.location: This is around the corner from Odub. Start up some blocks to gain the the solid rock.

climbs.name: One Bolt Wonder (unknown not a plaque)

content.description: Start to the left of the dirty red cam crack at a bolt. Climb bolt and move left into the crack and follow the dihedral to the two bolt anchor. The finish uses #0.75s and really fun!
content.protection: A double set from #0.1 to 0.75 with 2 extra #0.75s.

climbs.name: My Big 3 Inch (no plaque at bottom)

content.description: Climb the right-facing dihedral through the short roof onto the perfect splitter.
content.protection: One one 0.5 inch, one-two 2 inch pieces, four 3 inch pieces, and one 4 inch piece.
content.location: This is on the left side of Zappa Wall.

climbs.name: Muffin Man (aka Leaning Corner or Moderation)

content.description: The crux for most may be the beginning section where it can be awkward. After getting into the acute corner, it gets more secure. This is a good climb of decent length and varied sizes.
content.protection: Doubles in #0.5 and #0.75. Singles or doubles up to #2 Camalot.
content.location: This route is vaguely shown in the supplied picture. Scurry to up up canyon side of a small valley where there are three climbs. This is the leftmost of the three.

content.description:
This is the ever-widening offwidth dihedral to the left of the

Zig-Zag

route.
content.protection: Bring gear 3-6 inches.

climbs.name: Hands to OW Chimney (unknown due to no plaque)

content.description: Stem off the boulder into the left-leaning crack. Climb the hands to the 6 inch chimney to the ledge belay.
content.protection: Bring two 1 inch pieces, one 3 inch, one 5 inch, and one 6 inch.  We did the route with nothing bigger than a 3 inch piece, and it was very run out.
content.location: It is on the left side of Zappa Wall.

content.description:
Just to the right of the

Short Dihedral

in the chimney lies a crack that moves out the left side. It curves up the wall to anchors though half inch to 2 inch cams. It is amazing climbing up high on the pitch, and the bottom is not memorable.
content.protection: A double set from 0.4 to 2 inch.

content.description: Start up a bit of a rotten hand crack that gets slightly overhung. Pull into some fists in a clean corner. Keep chugging as it gets wider and wider. Towards the top, squeeze to the ledge and the anchors.
content.protection: Singles from #3 - #6. Doubles #2, #4 (just push the big cams).
content.location:
This is around the bend a bit from

Longer Corner

. It is probably a couple 100 yards climber's right. It is past the curving overhang called the Cobra.

climbs.name: Hanging to the Right (unknown due to no plaque)

content.description:
Head up the thin moves off the ramp to a zig-zag crack, and then climb right to the hand jams up top.

It is possible to exit to the left and follow the fingers up to the anchor also, 5.10.
content.protection: A single set from 0.2 to 2 inch one extra 2 inch piece.
content.location: This is on the left side of Zappa Wall.

climbs.name: The Frank Zappa Appreciation Society (aka Cobra Roof)

content.description: There are two cruxes after the initial 5.11- start. The first crux is an undercling right on tips to tips lieback. The second crux is an undercling campus out roof into ring locks to anchor.
content.protection: 1 bolt from original ascent and anchors, gear from 0.2-1 inch cams plus 1 draw. I used a number 1, 0.3, 0.5, and a draw on the send.
content.location:
It is in the middle of the Zappa Wall out the roof to the right of

Fork It

. The new trail takes you right to the climb.

content.description: Thin pinky jams from a Chinle band leads to a bigger size. Keep jamming up a widening crack as it gets steeper. You can get a hand in once in a while. When it gets steepest, it gets easier. It can be dirty.
content.protection: Blue Metolius. Doubles maybe triples through fingers and #0.75. Doubles #1 and one #2.
content.location:
This lies a hundred yards past

Big Hands Roof

and around the corner. It is the prominent, pale corner.

climbs.name: Green Cam Lieback (aka Pasta Maker, aka Brick Head)

content.description: Protect this with lots of green cams up the perfect dihedral. No rest comes until the dihedral disappears and it becomes a thin crack into a offwidth.
content.protection: 0.3-2 inch, 6-8 0.5 inch pieces.
content.location: This is the left-facing dihedral to the left of the pillar route.

content.description: Climb the left-facing flake to the ledge and two bolt anchor. It has fun jamming and liebacking to the top with great gear.
content.protection: Doubles from 0.4 to 3 inch with one 4 inch piece.
content.location:
This is just a few feet to the left of the

One Bolt Wonder

.

content.description:
Just to the left of the

Leaning Corner

is a hands to thin hands to fingers crack. A little runoff comes down the corner, so it looks dusty. It can be top roped if you climb the 5.8 and walk to the anchor on the other side (left). It's a good size to work, so don't be discouraged by a little dust on the wall. One run and it's pretty clean.

The climb goes to the top of the wall (I have not climbed it yet, but it looked like a fun adventure. I will eventually check it out to the top and find out. The top pitch(es) look clean and interesting).
content.protection: Gear from 0.4 to 2 inch (no more than 3 of each).
content.location: Climb up ten feet to a huge ledge and then walk to the corner and climb to ledge anchor. Lower off anchors to ground (the anchor is fine but needs new webbing and or chain).

content.description: This is a great climb with the crux right off of the deck. Finger jam high enough to sink a tight hand and continue up this tight hand/hands crack as it curves slightly to the left with the right side of the crack overlapping a bit. This climb is not to be missed!
content.location:
This lies seven feet right of

Short Corner

. Step across the gap.

content.description:
This ascends a corner system with many parallel cracks leading to the top (even though they are hidden).

It is to the right of the pillar at the far right side of the Zappa Wall. Start on some junky ledges until you begin climbing up a dihedral (protects with a small cam), then the route eases off to the top. Be aware of loose material on the route.
content.protection: Gear fingers to 2 inches.
content.location: It is the rightmost route on the wall, to the right of the pillar.

content.description: Through the ever present Chinle, do some small jams and crimps past the calcite. Climb fingers to a pod, then gun for the anchors where it gets really small....
content.protection: Finger size cams and maybe a nut at the beginning. The end gets down to green and blue Alien size.
content.location:
This is further right of

Hands to OW

, probably 200 yards. Turn the corner and you will see some calcite on a slab with a splitter and pod etched on to it. Climb it.

content.description:
Jesse Zacher and I checked this pitch out together and were both ready to overlook it for being too short and the start being too blank, but after both of us messed around on it, we realized that it had such unique movement that it had to be climbed.

This is a short, powerful crack. A thin and bouldery face section moves past a bolt to reach the thin crack. Finger locks get tighter as you move up and the main crack ends. Switch to the left seam past a 5 inch section to some balancy moves past the seam to the hand jam clip at the anchor.
content.protection: 1 quickdraw, #0 Metolius, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, 5 inch cam and a green Alien, optional 0.5 cam, two bolt anchor.
content.location:
This is a couple hundred yards to the left of the

Big Hands Roof

. Look for a big white piece of calcite at the base of the wall. There is another 5.11 OW in the corner to the right of this route in addition to a right-curving 5.11+ just a few feet to the right.

content.description: Start off working through a little overhang that can be tricky, but it is fun. Move into small hands to hands to the top.
content.protection: Bring doubles from medium fingers to #2 and a #3.
content.location: This lies around the corner by a large pillar that is leaning on the wall.
